responses.hobnob: "Hobnob" is one word: "Elected officials would hobnob with journalists at the annual gathering."
responses.runoff: Write "runoff" as one word when you're using it as a noun: "The candidates are headed for a runoff." Use two words for the verb: "He was able to run off with the money before anyone noticed the bag was missing."
responses.overtake: Use one word for "overtake": "Suddenly, the child overtook the runners and went on to place first."
responses.groundbreaking: Use one word for "groundbreaking": "The study described a groundbreaking discovery."
responses.onto: "Onto" is one word: "The designer did some last-minute tweaks before the models walked onto the runway."
responses.quarterfinal: Use one word for "quarterfinal" and "quarterfinalist": "The win means the team will advance to the quarterfinals."
responses.matchmaker: Use one word for "matchmaker" and "matchmaking": "They met through a friend who prided herself on her matchmaking skills."
responses.lighthearted: "Lighthearted" is one word: "Surprisingly, her wedding vows were very lighthearted."
responses.longtime: "Longtime" is one word as an adjective: "She's bringing her longtime boyfriend to the wedding." Otherwise, it's two words: "It has been a long time since I studied for a standardized test."
responses.kickoff: Write "kickoff" as one word when using it as a noun: "The students arrived early so they wouldn't miss kickoff." Write "kick off" as two words when using it it as a verb: "The first thing she does when she gets home is kick off her shoes."
responses.lineup: Use one word for "lineup" when you're using it as a noun: "Injuries continued to affect the team's starting lineup." Use two words for the verb: "People started to line up at 4 a.m."
responses.peacekeeping: "Peacekeeping" is one word: "They were hosting a special discussion about global peacekeeping efforts."
responses.anytime: "Anytime" is one word when used as an adverb: "Call me anytime!" Otherwise, it's two words: "I let it go to voicemail any time he calls."
responses.mifepristone: Don't capitalize "mifepristone," a medication used to end a pregnancy: "The judge's ruling on mifepristone put the drug's future in question."
responses.media: "Media" is plural and often should take plural verbs: "The media have varied in how they covered the story." However, it can sometimes take singular verbs, such as when you're referring to the media as one group: "The media is generally viewed unfavorably by Republicans."
responses.antebellum: Don't capitalize "antebellum" unless it's part of a proper noun: "Her paper focused on the economy of the antebellum South."
responses.massacre: "Massacre" describes a mass or unusually cruel murder, and unfortunately it is often an appropriate term for news stories. However, these events are horrible enough on their own and don't require the use of emotionally charged words, so limit use of the term as a noun. The adjective "mass" will often do. For example, use "mass shooting" instead of "shooting massacre." Avoid use of "massacre" as a verb. Instead of, "He massacred 50 people in the theater," write, "He killed 50 people in the theater."
responses.via: "Via" is a preposition, so lowercase it and don't use periods:  “He identified the attacker via a police sketch.”
responses.hackathon: Use one word for "hackathon": "The cofounders met at a hackathon."
responses.supermajority: "Supermajority" is one word: "There is virtually no chance the bill will make it past the California Legislature's Democratic supermajority."
responses.giddyup: Though the word "giddyup" originated as "giddap" and is also spelled "giddyap," use the "u" for clarity: "'Giddyup, let's go!' he yelled as he tried to get everyone out the door."
responses.democratic: Capitalize "Democratic" when you're using it as an adjective to refer to the political party: "The ranking member accused the Democratic committee members of engaging in a 'witch hunt.'" Do not capitalize it in other contexts: "The speaker of the House accused the president of violating democratic norms."
responses.shah: Like other titles, "shah" is capitalized when it comes directly before a name but not when it comes after a name or in general usage.
responses.selfie: The term "selfie" is widely known, so it's acceptable on first reference with no explanation required: "They took a selfie in front of the mural."
responses.genderqueer: "Genderqueer" refers to people who do not identify as strictly male or female. It is always one word: "As someone who is genderqueer, they were unable to complete the form because it only contained binary gender options."
responses.roofie: "Roofie" is slang for the generic sedative flunitrazepam, or Rohypnol, which is commonly associated with date rape. It's acceptable to use on the first reference if it's likely that your audience is familiar with the word. If not, use it only as appropriate with an explanation: "She thought someone put a sedative, commonly called a roofie, in her drink." It's common for "roofie" to be used as a verb, but opt for clarity by only using it in direct quotes: "Harrison said his friend was 'roofied and passed out' shortly after they left."
responses.sidepiece: "Sidepiece" is one word: "She wore a floral sidepiece in her hair for her wedding." Avoid using the term to refer to people unless someone identifies themself that way.
responses.amputation: Use "person with amputation" instead of "amputee:" "He worked as a podiatric surgeon and was a big advocate for people with amputations."
responses.sun: Don't capitalize "sun," even when referring to the Earth's sun: "After three straight days of rain, they were excited to see the sun come out." Use one word for "sunray," "sunrise" and "sunset": "They stayed outside until sunset."
responses.collab: You can use "collab" (no period) on first reference for "collaboration," especially if you're writing about music or quoting a source. However, if you think it will cause confusion, use "collaboration."
responses.burqa: A "burqa" is a garment worn by some Muslim women that covers the body and face. "She was a member of a group that was working to change burqa bans."
responses.superintendent: Only capitalize "superintendent" when it's a formal title coming directly before a name, and do not hyphenate it: "She was recently promoted to school district superintendent."
responses.mustache: "Mustache" and "moustache" are both correct spellings of the word, but "mustache" is more common in American English: "He grew a mustache after he left for college."
responses.reverend: When "reverend" is used as a religious title directly before a name, it can be abbreviated as "the Rev." Spell it out and do not capitalize it in other uses: "He went to the reverend for advice."
responses.dox: Use one "x" in "dox," "doxed" and "doxing," which is to post private information about someone online, often vengefully: "She was afraid if she posted anything else she would get doxed."
responses.host: "Host" is not capitalized, even when it comes directly before a name: "'Late Show' host Stephen Colbert insulted President Donald Trump in his monologue last night." Use "host" for all genders.
responses.meetup: "Meetup" is one word when you're using it as a noun: "She went to a meetup after class." It's two words if you're using the phrase as a verb: "She left class to meet up with her friends."
responses.ruble: Use "ruble" in all references to Russia's currency: "The skirt cost 950 rubles." (Its code is RUB.)
responses.maskless: "Maskless" is one word: "He was still uncomfortable being maskless even though he'd been vaccinated."
responses.bacteria: "Bacteria" is the plural form of "bacterium." However, it's OK to use with singular verbs: "The study indicates that gut bacteria is linked to mental health."
responses.subzero: "Subzero" is one word: "They weren't expecting subzero temperatures."
responses.kinda: Only use "kinda" if you are quoting someone. Otherwise, use "kind of."
responses.intersex: Use "intersex" to describe someone born with chromosomes, genitalia and/or reproductive organs that fall outside standard definitions of male and female: "She is one of the intersex athletes speaking out about the new rules." Do not use the term "hermaphrodite."
responses.wannabe: "Wannabe" is one word, no hyphen: “The clique of girls at school saw Jackie as a wannabe.”
responses.decathlon: Do not capitalize "decathlon": "She's part of the effort to get women's decathlon in the Olympics."
responses.stake: Use "stake" for phrases such as "stake a claim," "at stake," "stake one's life" and "stake out": "'I'd bet a lot of money, but I wouldn't stake my life on it,' she said."
responses.salary: Don't include salary or net worth in a story unless it's directly relevant. Use numerals when doing so: "She asked for more pay when she realized her $60,000 annual salary was $15,000 less than a male coworker in the same role." Remember that salary is one type of compensation. Don't use it to refer to hourly wages, bonuses, stock options, etc.
responses.daycare: Use one word for "daycare": "We wanted to find our son a daycare."
responses.thundersnow: Use one word for "thundersnow," the rare weather phenomenon in which snow falls instead of rain during a thunderstorm: "Despite their name, thundersnows are relatively quiet affairs since snow muffles the sound of the thunder."
responses.mouthpiece: Use one word for "mouthpiece": "She accused him of being an uncritical mouthpiece for the party in power."
responses.vlog: A “vlog” is a video blog or video log: “Many YouTubers post daily vlogs about their lives.”
responses.chairperson: Use one word for "chairperson," and use it or "chair" instead of "chairman" or "chairwoman": "As chair, she led all the committee meetings." Don't capitalize unless it's a formal title coming directly before a name: "He introduced Chair Shelly Engel."
responses.bedsheet: Use one word for "bedsheet": "He realized he forgot to change the bedsheets in the guest room."
responses.county: Capitalize "county" when you use it as part of the proper name of a county: "Los Angeles County is America's most populous county." Lowercase it when not using it as part of a proper noun: "The county of Los Angeles is America's most populous county."
responses.skateboard: Use one word for "skateboard," "skateboarder" and "skateboarding": "He's a skateboarder who's competing in one of the first Olympic skateboarding events."
responses.keto: Do not capitalize "keto" when referring to the popular diet: "He swore by the keto diet, because it helped him lose 50 pounds."
responses.kitty-corner: Use "kitty-corner" to describe objects that are diagonally across from each other: "The building is kitty-corner from the parking lot." Variants of the word include "catty-corner" and "catercorner," but "kitty-corner" is most commonly used.
responses.whiskey: Use "whiskey" for the drink: "She would add a little whiskey to her tea when she was sick."
responses.scuba: Use two words for "scuba diving" and "scuba diver": "After years of being afraid of the water, they finally conquered the fear by going scuba diving." Fun fact: "Scuba" is an acronym for "self-contained underwater breathing apparatus."
responses.funnyperson: Use one word for “funnyperson,” “funnyman” and “funnywoman” when referring to comedians. Default to gender-neutral language unless the person you are writing about has expressed a particular preference or their gender identity is well known: “Chelsea Handler used to have late-night show, and more recently, the funnywoman was on tour to promote her latest book.” Only "funnyman" is widely recognized as a word, but extending the recognition to “funnyperson” and “funnywoman” allows for greater parity. Use two words if you're not referring to a comedian: "'She's always making jokes,' he said. 'She's a funny woman.'"
responses.breakdance: Use one word for "breakdance" and "breakdancing": "She wanted to sign up for breakdancing lessons." The new Olympic sport is officially known as "breaking": "He hopes to take home the first-ever Olympic gold medal for breaking."
